## device_type (deprecated)

Property name: `device_type`

Value type: `<string>`

The _device_type_ property was used in IEEE 1275 to describe the device's FCode programming model. Because the Devicetree Specification does not have FCode, new use of the property is deprecated, and it should be included only on `cpu` and `memory` nodes for compatibility with IEEE 1275–derived devicetrees.'s FCode programming model. Because the Devicetree Specification does not have FCode, new use of the property is deprecated, and it should be included only on `cpu` and `memory` nodes for compatibility with IEEE 1275–derived devicetrees.

For `memory` nodes the value shall be `"memory"`. For `cpu` nodes the value shall be `"cpu"`.

```dts
/* arch/arm/boot/dts/aspeed-g5.dtsi */
memory@80000000 {
    device_type = "memory";
    reg = <0x80000000 0x0>;
};

/* arch/arm64/boot/dts/qcom/sm8550.dtsi */
cpu0: cpu@0 {
    device_type = "cpu";
    reg = <0x0 0x0>;
};
```

---

**Source:** Linux kernel Documentation\n\n```\n - device_type: Must be "cpu".
 - compatible: Must be "mti,interaptiv".
 - reg: CPU number.
 - clocks: Must include the CPU clock.  See ../../clock/clock-bindings.txt for
   details on clock bindings.
Example:
	cpus {
		#address-cells = <1>;
		#size-cells = <0>;\n```
